commentText: These type of low level people love to tell other people how much they make illegally. But what they don't tell you is that they barely make ends meet where they live and they are often quoting higher numbers which are not true. 2500 euro per month even if true can never make you 'rich' in Europe. And you have to work your ass off doing low level jobs just to earn that much in cash and also there nothing you can do if someone cheats you or refuses to pay you money after a job is done because it's all illegal. I can't count how many times I have seen this happen where cash job people are eventually cheated on due to their gullible position. In these circumstances such people with no real job and no real future, often like to tell people back home or gullible newly arrived Indians how they make so much money in rupees. But the truth is they are not buying groceries or paying rent in rupees. They are doing it in their local currencies. I don't know how many people who have bragged in front of me in all these years, when I enquired about their circumstance with specific questions, exposed that they were in a real shitty situation with no future and the danger of being deported anytime. Never believe such one sided stories especially. Nobody is becoming rich without putting proper hard work and working legally especially in European and western countries.

commentText: I once got fired from my dishwasher job for trying to call off sick. Was working there for over a year, and it was my 1st time calling out. He assured me I had a case, and that it was a guaranteed victory, but since I'd only just recently become full time, I hadn't made enough for the settlement to have been worth the lawyer fees. commentText: In New Zealand, there is a dismissal process and a good reason must be given, otherwise the employer can be sued. Here, healthcare is not tied to your job either, as most medical things are covered by the government anyway, except about $60 for GP visits. commentText: Complimentary tech does end up eliminating farm workers. If you have 20 farmhands, but you can make 4 of them 400% more effective, you now have 4 people doing the work that it used to take all 20 to do.   This is fine if you're business can expand, but if it can't, you have an excess 16 farmhands who don't need to be on the payroll.  It is literally the purpose of technology to reduce the amount of work it takes to do things. Businesses would never adopt a technology that increases the amount of laborvalue it takes to do the same task.

videoDescription: To get free fractional shares worth up to 100 EUR, you can open an account with Trading 212 through this link ...
commentText: A few thoughts.  For reference,  I teach industrial automation technologies how to set up, program, maintain and troubleshoot mechanical automation systems.  Setting up robotic assembly lines, building machines that build machines, etc.   I began teaching only a few years ago after many years in industry.   1. I was in the middle of the hollowing out of American manufacturing. Sometimes didn't know if I'd have a job next month because the plant was moving to overseas.  Also had to deal with many problems with parts and quality after those moves - and having to deal with supply chain when companies would decide to move their lines, but not build a product that directly replaced the one they quit making.  The corporate bottom line looked good, but the headaches from the people left was horrible, and worse, the devastation of the middle class was and is a reality.   2. The middle class is what made the US economy so strong, and it's a hollowed out shell.   Used to be, pretty much any job that wasn't flipping burgers was paying much more than minimum wage, and we didn't expect people to  go their entire lives on that pay.  It was for the kids in high school working part time or someone just out of school who was getting the entry level job that, in a month, or 3 or 6 was making much more than that.  Seriously, 20 years ago, minimum wage full time was less than 1% of the working population.   Actual middle class jobs were 75% of jobs (or more) and paid 10x that amount - AND you could afford to buy a car every couple of years, buy a house, and not have to go into future wage debt with credit cards.   Nowadays, people are trying to keep up appearances, but the US middle class is BROKE.    3. Companies have largely forgotten how to be loyal to employees. Used to be, you could get a job at age 20 or 25 and realistically could work there until retirement. And GROW, not just do the same job for 40 years.  The coming of the "gig economy" and the teaching by business schools of "interchangeable economic units" from a  Human Resources department had done a lot of the damage here.  Used to be, most middle and large sized companies had a significant training program in place where they would teach employees not only how to do their job, but also give them paths of advancement.   The disconnect between Wall Street and Main Street has choked that out.  For a long time,  you get hired for a job, and if you want a raise or a position advancement, you move somewhere else, instead of growing inside the company.    That seems to be changing a little... but not much. 4. These large tech corporations have done a marvelous job of publicly spreading risk while privately holding wealth - LLMs especially have been ripping off a lot of people from copyright, that, if it had been the other way, would have had the people getting sued - but the government has let the software companies get away with this "for the greater good" - even though it's pretty clear that LLMs are going to hurt a lot of people by not giving them a way into being productive. 5. Another dangerous thing about LLM - if it takes away the entry level "easy" tasks that are the training/honing tools for people to get good at, say, spotting cancers or other medical things - what happens in 10 or 20 years when all the current experts all die off? Who fills their shoes? If no one is allowed to get better because the job doesn't exist any more - then when there comes a time for the people to be there - where are they coming from?     Honestly, my field is the one area in manufacturing that still his hiring a lot of people - and we've kind of gone through that #5 part already - for many years the maintenance people didn't hire anyone because "well, we've got Bob, and Bob knows everything" - until Bob retires, or worse, drops dead from a heart attack...  now no one knows how to maintain the machines.  Smart companies have started waking up to that, and I keep praying the rest of industry does as well - but we've let too much money wreck the safeguards of government - and too many are focused on next quarter instead of next year or 5 years...   Meanwhile, I'm going to train as many people as I can, because when the robots do rise up, the people best able to defeat them are the ones who know how they work.

commentText: I worked at the intersection of strategic workforce planning, workforce development, and technology for over ten years. The assumption that we can just retrain everybody runs into serious problems every time I've seen it tested. (1) Many people in their 40's and 50's like what they were trained to do and are reasonably good at it. It isn't easy to tell someone who loves, let's say, working with animals, and tell them "Sorry, now you have to become an architect." (2) Many people, after 10-20 years of work experience, become pretty good at doing the EXACT JOB THEY ALREADY HAVE but would be pretty useless if asked to do anything else, even jobs that, on paper, look like the same job. (3) For the most part, people already have the most mentally / intellectually demanding job they can perform. Do not assume you can take a reasonably smart supply chain analyst who hasn't been to school in 15+ years and tell them "We'll train you to teach English in Japan, since AI can't do that yet." (4) Pretty soon, AI will be teaching English in Japan, so then what do you tell your ex-supply chain analyst ex-foreign English teacher to do then? Even if reskilling worked perfectly, it would take 3-5 years per reskilling.

commentText: I think a big part of why it‚Äôs not being talked about, is because a lot of people don‚Äôt see it as any different than the longstanding [it was already being parodied in _Office Space_ (1999) ] corporate trend of dumping employees in favor of contractors with no benefits. So this was already a huge problem, and the inclusion of foreign contractors in countries with significantly lower costs of living changes it, but doesn‚Äôt _dramatically_ change it. It‚Äôs an acceleration, not an inflection point.   Which doesn‚Äôt mean that it‚Äôs not bad or not worth talking about. And the acceleration can make a thing that was a minor problem around the edges into a society-undermining problem. But most humans are very bad at recognizing creeping threats, very bad at planning for nebulous threats, and bad-to-very-bad at cognitive empathy. So I think the lack of conversation reflects lack of recognizing that this is a systemic problem. Thanks for bringing it up!  But I also think this reflects factionalism and lack of much trans-national worker solidarity to counterbalance the power of transnational corporations. In the US, big transnational corporations and some politicians have for 50+ years mostly succeeded in scapegoating workers in lower-COL countries and pitting US workers against them. Most of the US unions completely fell for this in the 1970s-1990s, pushing to prevent offshoring of manufacturing jobs through contracts and legislation, instead of pushing to unionize the foreign workers. They saw foreign workers as unfair  competition instead of recognizing the corporations and shareholders as the source of the problem.

commentText: Italian here, you did an excellent job  explaining almost everything, but I would like to add another two things. Firstly, in many cases (but not always and there are many nuances) there is a toxic work culture whereby young people are "forced" to accept unfair conditions because otherwise the employers may argue that "young people just think about partying and aren't willing to make any sacrifices" (this is quite a common narrative here). Secondly, because Italy's population is quite old (and other factors), young people often find a stagnant environment, both economically and socially, shall I say, which can be suffocating. There are many things which could be said, but please look at the graph in 3:12. The regions of Emilia-Romagna and Lombardy receive many internal immgitants, because of the prestige of the oldest university in Europe and the financial capital of Italy respectively, which contribute to a more dynamic environment. On the other hand, (mainly) southern regions, which already have many issues to begin with and therefore a monotonous environment, see a large proportion of their young people leaving for other regions or other countries

commentText: I think you overlooked two major issues: 1. Recent graduates are often mistreated in our toxic work environments. They‚Äôre forced to either conform, push back and risk becoming toxic themselves, or leave the country. 2. There may be no pension system left for younger generations. The state pension plan, INPS, is often called a Ponzi scheme. Each generation funds the pensions of the current retirees, but workers are now outnumbered by pensioners. This makes the system unsustainable and likely to collapse within a couple of decades, leaving today‚Äôs young workers without a pension. People who are educated, speak a second language, and have in-demand skills are wisely seizing opportunities to leave as soon as they can.

commentText: I'm Italian, 24 years old, and lucky enough to work in the aviation industry, a field I‚Äôm passionate about, and one that pays relatively well. But even here, in what should be one of the most structured and respected sectors, the system is broken.  I graduated high school with 100/100, but still struggled to find meaningful work. My first job? Stocking shelves in an Amazon warehouse, because I had no experience, and few companies are willing to take a chance on someone fresh out of school. Eventually I made it into my field. And yes, I agree that aviation must have strict exams and standards, people‚Äôs lives are at stake. But even within major national institutions like ENAV, which manages all of Italy‚Äôs airspace, there are practices that, in my honest opinion, are just scummy.  Legally, you can only be employed on fixed-term contracts for 24 months total for the same role and employer. After that, the company must either justify the extension with a valid cause or convert it to a permanent (indefinite) contract. You‚Äôre only allowed four renewals, and there must be mandatory breaks between rehirings (10‚Äì20 days depending on contract length).  So what do companies do?  -they hire people for short stints (3 to 6 months) to avoid going over those thresholds; -they avoid calling it a renewal, even when you‚Äôre doing the exact same job, to bypass the limit on renewals; -they warn you upfront: "You can work here for a maximum of 2 or 3 years, then you're out."; -they require you to resubmit documents like ID, bank info, and criminal records each time, treating you like a new hire, even when you're returning after just a few weeks.  Yes, some of this is tied to compliance with security regulations or bureaucratic HR policies. But let‚Äôs be real: a lot of it is by design. The system is built to stay legal, tick the boxes for safety or anti-fraud, but still make it as easy as possible to avoid giving workers indefinite contracts (with all the protections, severance, and obligations that come with them).  How can a young person look at this and not want something better? How can someone not want a more stable, reliable and secure future for himself, and potential partner + family? Even "nerds" like me who poured over books, and were top of the class, are not safe from loopholes. All my life I've been told "just work hard and things will come"... My hard work got me in the field I studied for, but these fields were supposed to be different from the vast majority which take advantage of workers.  It was a rough wakeup call to realize even the dream places you wish to work at, follow the same tricks.  As long as the laws benefit the companies, and not the worker, the workers will of course go somewhere more stable.

commentText: I'm a Dane, and here's why I'm a happy tax payer.  At 17, I started suffering from debilitating chronic stomach pain, which lasted until I was 23, when I was finally diagnosed and got the right medication. In a matter of 2-3 years, I was symptom free, and in a few more years, I felt that the mental issues developed from living with a chronic disease had finally settled. At 31, I am living a completely normal life. I have critiques of the Danish healthcare system for some mismanagement of my disease (why did I have to suffer for 6 years?) but this isn't about my critiques, but my praise:  Due to my illness, it took me 8,5 years to finish a master's that should've taken 5,5 (managed to do the Master's on the numerated 2 after going through treatment and was so proud of that). Had I lived in the states, I would've been royally fucked. I would've had to drop my education or become severely indebted. As I had to study on less than full time, for obvious reasons, I couldn't have a job on the side - I could barely manage my studies. I was dependent on the student subsidies given to every student, as well as the low-rate loan available to students. I never had to stress about that part of the issue. I could stress about whether I'd ever be well again, whether I'd be able to hold down a job, etc. etc., but I NEVER DOUBTED I WOULD LIVE. Even if I'd have had to embrace a life of being severely disabled and living off the smallest subsidies, I would still have survived, I would still get medical aid, because in Denmark, we take care of each other.  Now, I'm on the other side and have worked full-time for 2 years at a well-paid job. I pay my high taxes happily, because I was given this opportunity, I was given that help, and that faith. I want to pass that on to others, and I want Denmark to remain a state where we are equal, where we all have basic human rights, where nobody is left in the gutter. When I calculate how much I've paid in taxes so far, I don't feel sad at lost money, I feel pride at my contribution.

commentText: I am danish, and while we love to complain about taxes, one cannot deny how much value we get for it. Schools are great, hospitals are modern and wait lists are usually not long, our roads are mostly in great condition. I can get to a doctor usually within 2-3 days, sometimes even same day. While I like to complain we pay a lot of taxes, its a lot better than the alternative. I would much rather live in a place where taxes benefit everyone, rather than me having 20% more income to spend on expensive health insurance, and seeing suffering everywhere. Only place we lack is military, but being a tiny country that is a given really. We have 27 F35 jets, which is a lot for us when our active personelle is only 25k, its 5.4 F-35 pr million people, where the US has 1.7 F-35 pr million people. So while volume is lower, its a lot for us really.

commentText: I want to make one correction to the lady around 9:17. The word you're looking for is "automated tracking system" or ATS. Examples include Workday and Talio. These are not new and as a 32 year old when I graduated when I was younger I encountered them as well (circa 2015-2016). ATS systems have nothing to do with the impact ChatGPT and generative AI has on the labour market and it's not helpful to confuse the two. People have been complaining about ATS systems for a very long time, even before ChatGPT and the like existed. The time when humans would review applications was a very long time ago, like maybe 2010 or thereabouts.

commentText: The housing collapse was the first crack. Banks gambled, collapsed, and got taxpayer bailouts. Executives handed themselves bonuses with public money while the public paid the price. Occupy Wall Street tried to push back, but nothing truly changed. The same players stayed in power. The rules stayed rigged.  Now we are living through the next phase. Mass layoffs, ghost jobs, AI filters, and stagnant wages are everywhere. Profits soar, shareholders celebrate, and executives cash out while telling workers to be grateful for scraps.  Meritocracy is gone. Optics replaced it. Corporate success is no longer built on value or skill, but on who can perform the best image while cutting the people they parade for PR. Behind the curtain, the human element is gone, and the fa√ßade grows thicker.  AI is not the enemy. The real danger is AI CEOs and executives who treat technology as their personal crown. They are not building; they are competing to out-narcissist each other, blinded by ego and greed. Investors fuel this arms race because it spikes their portfolios, no matter the long-term damage. Behind closed doors, the C-suite and shareholders pat themselves on the back while carving out what remains of the middle class.  This is not about politics. It is about power. The ultra-wealthy control the levers and have no interest in building a system that works for anyone else. This is the second reckoning. The first was the manufacturing carve-out that gutted entire communities. This one is a technological carve-out, and its effects are already eroding the workforce from within.  If you feel invisible, you are not imagining it. This market is not broken; it is built to extract and discard. Until people stop accepting optics for progress and demand substance, the machine will keep grinding through generation after generation.  The ultra-wealthy will not save us. They are too busy competing to see who can burn it down the fastest.

commentText: it's the K shaped economy that's the root of all this. we let wealth inequality get so out of control that if the bottom 60% stopped all their consumer spending in its entirety, you'd only see a 20% reduction in purchases across the economy (a mild recession, but not catastrophic). at the same time, even a few % decrease in spending by the top 20% and the entire economy collapses. this has forced businesses and governments to create policy around that upper sector, and largely ignore the bottom 60% because, in economic terms, theyre irrelevant. theyre too poor and have too little purchasing power to cater to.   this is what happened in the 1880s-1920s, and it's happening again. the difference is today we can just replace the productive capacity of the bottom with automation. people really dont understand how bad this will get. even in the 1930s, despite massive government intervention, the economy never recovered. it took a world war to pull the US out of the slump, because a world war forced a redistribution of wealth (high taxes to pay for the war effort, followed by financial repression on those who own assets and a need for mass mobilization of the population which led to political concessions to guarantee cooperation) which reset the game. we're headed towards a feudalism with robots, or revolution. maybe both.

commentText: When a company wants 3-5 years of experience for an entry level job: 1. They aren't actually hiring. They're posting jobs pad the "jobs created" numbers. They're going to use it as leverage to say "they can't find qualified people" and pressure the government to allow them to hire more non-citizens on visa for cheaper (ex: the H1B visa program). OR, they're going to use it as an excuse for diving more into automation to justify replacing those jobs with AI and make someone at the company look good by "solving a problem" with AI.  2. They don't want people fresh out of school. You've all probably seen the BS reasons given for this. Look it up if you haven't, but there are companies that don't want to hire Gen Z workers fresh out of school right now. They often won't come out and say it because they don't want to spend money handling the backlash, but it's essentially what they're doing. As a reminder, age discrimination is LEGAL for anybody under 40. It's not until you hit age 40 and above that you now have a legal right against age discrimination in the US.  3. They're keeping wages down. Someone with 3-5 years of work experience is worth more than an entry level job salary, but if they can't get a higher position somewhere, they'll have to take the lower paying "entry level" position even if the "other duties as assigned" aspect of the job is actually something that would normally be done at a higher position. The reason why this is significant is because wages DO get tracked. Companies look at that data and think about ways they can squeeze more work out of every individual and if they can spread some work normally done by someone in a higher position among entry level workers to "give them experience" while keeping the amount they pay to get that work done lower, they consider it as "win/win". The bright eyed, eager entry level worker gets more exposure and experience and the company gets to pay less to get the work done. Now they can use AI to take more of the work load as well.  This isn't anything new. The same thing happened in the fallout of the dotcom bubble bust in the early 2000s. Younger GenX and older Millenials went through the same thing. Even before AI, people were writing software for automation. It IS unfair. It ruined those people's lives and prevented them from having a good start after school. Millions of people were screwed just by the timing of them entering the workforce. There was NO help for them. There will be NO help for GenZ entering the workforce today. In addition to that millions of other older workers had their careers destroyed as well. It was a dark time and then just as things showed signs of getting better, the Great Recession happened in the late 2000s.  Today, we're also heading to a major recession. It's a VERY bad sign when AI spending from few companies is literally propping up the US economy right now. The writing is on the wall. This situation may improve somewhat for a few people who finally break into the workforce, but a recession is coming to knock them and everyone else down.  I REALLY wish there was a better outlook coming, but there isn't. All any of us can do (young and older workers alike) is keep on trying. Giving up won't pay the bills or put food on the table. After we get through the coming dark times, things will eventually get better for everyone, but we have to keep trying and sometimes fight to get there.

commentText: I'm an engineer from Romania working and living in Germany for more than 8 years now. When I came over I did so with a direct contract, though, I did invest time in learning the language at least to a B2 level when I considered looking for a job here. And, while I have 8 years here, my language skills are far from what I want them to be, so I still, periodically, do language courses. Since then, with COVID and the drop in German Automotive industry, my company closed but my CEO collected a few of us and started a new one. So, in my 8 years, I collected unemployment for only 1 month. Switching out of the Automotive industry (where my main experience was) took about 1.5 - 2 years of constant learning, interviewing and self-correcting. I had a lot of interviews where I got to the end stage of the process but it took time, attention to what I could improve after each interview and a significant amount of energy and research. So, work through it, I'm not saying its 100% going to happen, but chances for skilled workers, with German language skills (even poor ones), are quite good in my experience. As for German bureaucracy, I come from Romania :) Germany does have more bureaucracy but I find it's functional and quite efficient. The social and taxation systems would probably not work as well without it. However, I do think a lot is over-regulated here and this is consistent with the opinion of my German colleagues :).  What feel is missing and is becoming problematic is digitalization and quality of services. Most, from state provided services (finance, medical, city offices), to private, service oriented, businesses like banks and telecommunication are outdated, overpriced and of mediocre quality.  All in, Germany is, for me, a lot better than Romania, the caveat being: your family and long-time friends are now a long way away. This is not a small factor in your quality of life. There are a lot of things to improve, but this is as much a chance as an issue, since you can be part of improving some aspects and helping your adoptive country.

commentText: Just one thing to add: childcare is not free in every German federal state.   The one thing that baffles me is that many are surprised that bureaucracy is in German (paperwork / administration  and so forth).  I am German and I have not only lived in Germany, but also in 2 other countries, but at no point have I ever expected to be accommodated in English or in German. The idea did not even occur in my mind. In fact I had learned the languages before going there and dedicated a lot of time and money to it so I could actually achieve a certificated C1 level for one country and a C2 for the other.  I don't think you absolutely need that I believe you will probably get by with a B2 level, but at the least you should have a B1 level.  It is one thing if you fled from another country, then you really have no chance to prepare for this, but if you actively choose a country, no matter which one, you absolutely do have the chance to prepare and you absolutely should!  Personally I believe that speaking the language also will let you have a completely different experience and make life, social interactions and everything so much easier. I would not underestimate the power of language.

commentText: I've been to Walmart for 2 years.  It's tough. Even at minimum wage, I had management riding me nonstop to be faster every night I worked.  This was a minimum wage job, yet they treated it like Amazon warehouse where they keep pushing you every day you work to be faster and do more in less time.  I was written up for the dumbest stuff.  One night I was stocking I had 4 mixed pallets on one end of my aisle and 1 pallet of just my stuff at the other.  Management called me to the office and said they're writing me up for not working because that 1 pallet is still sitting there at the end of my aisle.  I explained he obviously didn't see the other 4 mixed pallets which my stuff on top buried everyone else's stuff underneath so I was trying to move that off and stock it because you're not supposed to leave boxes strewn across the floor.  Management said they didn't see it and apologized, but said they still had to write me up because they had already called me to the office and it would look bad on them for pulling me away from my work for nothing.  That was back in 2015.  I'm sure Walmart is a lot harder today.  I changed jobs went to a grocery store doing minimum wage.  The grocery store refused to provide benefits, so everyone was scheduled less than 20hrs/wk.  I had just graduated from college (in my 30s) and had 10 years of customer service/retail exp under my belt and they treat me like I'm below the high school kids they were hiring that sit around drinking gatorade and playing on their phones.  Anyway, minimum wage jobs for the past 10 years couldn't afford an apartment, and I'm sure nowadays they can't either.  My old apartment up near the university was across the street from the grocery store used to be $600/month.  Today, it's practically doubled in rent, and the neighborhood now has a lot of problems with drugs.  A nice apartment in that university town you're looking at paying $3k+ for a single.  I left to China in 2019 because I couldn't find a job with my BA degree from the university right there in that town.  The Career Center at the university kept telling me to apply for GEICO insurance because they just opened new offices and needed help.  Her husband worked there.  I applied and went through round 1 of interviews 3 times.  They always ghost me after that.  So one day I called GEICO and asked to speak with the HR because I really wanted to know yes or no whether I got the job.  They told me the HR will be working on Thursdays.  I called back on Thursday, and the HR was out of town down in Florida on a family vacation.  I'm sitting there like, "you could have told me she was going to be out of the office this thursday, call back next thursday, but you didn't."  Felt like they just were making up stories and the job postings on Indeed might have been fake to appear like they're hiring when they were not.  I was also upset with the career center for not helping me find work.  You would think the school would be helping graduates find work because it'd show that their university degrees actually have value!  Instead, they didn't help me.  I had to go out and find my own job teaching in China.  I wish I could end there, but covid started 6 months after I arrived.  Their visa situation was chaos and my visa expired during a lockdown, so I couldn't get another work visa and I had to return home.  Now I'm jobless, living at home, taking care of my grandmother that was recently diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease.  If she goes into a nursing home, we'll lose the house.  I've tried finding work when I came home from China, but employers just laugh me out the door.  The only type of job hiring right now is heavy industrial, and I don't have any heavy industrial skills.  I'm an academic, not a tradesman.  You say the job market is on the edge?  I'd say it's already collapsed when even young generation are struggling to find entry level positions and salaries everywhere are not keeping up with inflation and the rising cost of living.

commentText: After 28 years of living in Canada, we finally moved to Cannes, France. The beautiful weather, fantastic Mediterranean cuisine, and polite people have made our transition enjoyable. We also appreciate the opportunity to travel by train whenever we want. My only regret is that we did not make this move earlier.   Obtaining a long-stay visa was straightforward; it allows us to stay for a year without the need to relocate every time. We can reapply for this visa annually, and after five years, we will be eligible for permanent residency.   We purchased medical insurance for both of us, which cost C$1,400 for one year. A doctor's visit costs ‚Ç¨80, making healthcare very affordable here.

commentText: I moved to Bulgaria as a self-employed EU national. It's not at all like moving from California to Idaho; there is quite a process to go through. Incl. depositing 12x mininum local salary, buying private health insurance, etc. I had to apply for a Bulstat number, and to do that you are required to go through local lawyers/accountants. Good ones are hard to find and charge a lot; plus they love to unexpectedly up their fees by 20%-30% because "inflation."  The income tax I pay is 10% minus 4% flat expenses = 6%. Sounds fantastic. Except the mandatory social security contributions are ‚Ç¨600 per month (regardless of whether you‚Äôve had any income during that month or not). In much wealthier Czech/Slovakia, those are about ‚Ç¨200 per month. And if you are a day late with the payments, the government is already charging you interest/penalty.  Lastly, I bought a one-bedroom condo unit. A "management company" swooped in and started charging ‚Ç¨700+ in annual maintenance fees. For that, they provide nothing. No service contract and no one as much as mops the floor  outside my apartment all year long. On top of that, they're now in court with another "management company." Depending on the outcome, I may have to pay the fees a second time, all over again.  1 liter of milk costs ‚Ç¨1 in Austria, ‚Ç¨0.69 in Slovakia. My local Billa sells it for ‚Ç¨2.00 - local Bulgarian milk, mind you. A 100-mile taxi ride to the airport, in my old country, sets you back ‚Ç¨80; here it's ‚Ç¨150. And that's before the upcoming switch to euro in January 2026.  So that's a foreigner's life in Bulgaria. A safe, peaceful place, stunning flora, low taxes, Russian and English widely understood, a stone's throw to Greece... And also a lot of screwy stuff and strong-arm tactics.

commentText: As a european (German): as said in the video, you don't go to Europe because of low fees. You will pay a lot for the system (maybe there are some exceptions like Bulgaria). People with wealth are hit relatively hard (in terms of their wealth). But i definitely think the quality of life is great. I think a lot of people downplay the safety, cleanliness and services you can get. Now yes, you may find some more safe and clean places in Asia. But we have a good package too i would say. Things are always subjective. I can't really stand heat / above 24¬∞c, i like cold weather. I can't imagine myself living in a permanent tropical climate. For other people this sounds like a dream. So maybe Finland or Iceland would be more suitable to me and Malaysia or Oman to someone else. It'll be hard to find vegan food in Asia, in most of Europe that's pretty easy. Not many people will care about this but personally i do. It all has its ups and downs. If you are poor it's "great" (in quotes of course - being poor is obviously never great, but relatively speaking in comparison to other places). If you are so rich that you hardly care about the taxes and fees you gotta pay it's great for the quality of life. If you are somewhere in between i can see the reservations to be honest. Of course we are not a country, so every country within Europe is its own thing, we just share a lot of values. Especially places that are close together geographically of course.

commentText: About bringing your spouse with you to EU countries, you mentioned Italy and Austria but I have dealt with both as I have both of those citizenships...  In Italy, yes, you can just bring your spouse.  He / She can get a 5 year spousal visa with no language requirements.  Then the spouse can upgrade to permanent residency.  Austria, on the other hand, requires your spouse to have an A1 German language certificate as a start to get a 1 year visa to stay with you.  If your spouse resists wanting to learn another language, this can make it harder to keep the family together.  (this situation only applies if your spouse is NOT an EU citizen otherwise they have the right of free movement without further language restrictions)  If I am not mistaken, when that visa comes up for renewal after only one year, the spouse has to up the skills to A2 German to show that "integration" is progressing.  Like Italy, at the 5 year mark, the spouse can go for permanent residency.  Separately but related to language...  If you come from the US, Austria will let you convert your driver's license to an Austrian one which will then be valid for driving in all of the EU.  Even if you started from scratch, Austria will let you take the classes in English or German.  However, Italy will only let you drive on your US license for 1 year.  Then you MUST start from scratch and go through Italian driver's education in Italian with no option to do it in English.  Just a couple of things to keep in mind.
